{"id":14881857,"mediaExerciseId":"1677cf91-424d-454c-9600-47b5cc6b810f","exerciseName":"7","chapterName":"24","chapterTitle":"Options and Corporate Finance","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"24.7","sectionTitle":"Options and Corporate Securities","pageNumber":819,"solutions":[{"id":5999783,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will learn about warrants, options, and convertible bonds.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define call option.\n\n**Call Option** is the right of a holder to buy a stock.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":136,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f0c5161b74bee48b82f504622238d31e/4be7712b218f9be012c9e57d2ba42813/lateximg_large.png","width":999},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f0c5161b74bee48b82f504622238d31e/4be7712b218f9be012c9e57d2ba42813/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"### How are warrants and call options different.\n\nIn a call option, the holder has the right but not the obligation to buy the underlying asset at a specific price, wherein a stock warrant gives the holder the right to avail the specific number of shares at a specific price and date.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f0c5161b74bee48b82f504622238d31e/aac2f102dff995f29508d994090ae910/lateximg_large.png","width":732},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f0c5161b74bee48b82f504622238d31e/aac2f102dff995f29508d994090ae910/lateximg.png","width":366}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"### What is the minimum value of a convertible bond.\n\nThe minimum value of a convertible bond is the present value of future annual interest payments plus the principal repayment from the bond or the \"investment value\" of its bond component.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"### Explain how car insurance acts like a put option.\n\nCar insurance acts like a put option because the insurance holder can demand payment for the exercise price from the company.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"### Explain why U.S. government loan guarantees are not free.\n\nU.S. government loan guarantees are not free because of the put option given to the holders of risky bonds.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"40d4200a-6d8e-4934-a835-f7fbf8d45f47","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881858,"exerciseName":"1","page":822,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"b0d940e5-690b-4dca-860f-1f5eb33fa3b0","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fun